<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10055e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10055e">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10055e"> 55(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> desk lady / work dodger</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[O]</font>n peut &hellip; y <font color="green">[= dans les Hotels des Postes, construits pour l&apos;administration du <i>Reichs-Postamt</i>]</font> faire sa correspondance, seul, &agrave; l&apos;abri du regard indiscret d&apos;un voisin, sans g&ecirc;ner personne, sous la seule surveillance des employ&eacute;s plac&eacute;s &agrave; d&eacute;couvert devant un large comptoir et non derri&egrave;re un grillage m&eacute;tallique entrelac&eacute; d&apos;&eacute;tiquettes administratives, dont la plus connue indique que le <i>guichet est ferm&eacute;,</i> <mark>pour que le guichetier ait le temps de se limer les ongles</mark>, tout en lisant les nouvelles du jour dans son journal favori. <font color="green">[In the Post Offices constructed for the administration of the Reichspostamt, one can write one&apos;s letters, safe from the prying eyes of one&apos;s neighbours and without interrupting anybody. All one encounters is the supervision of clerks, seated in full view in front of a large counter and not behind a wire netting tagged with notices, most notoriously the one that says that <i>the booth is closed</i> so that the desk clerk may have time to file his nails while reading the news in his favourite paper.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) ?165-6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
